1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:04,562
# AI Weekly #20/2026

2
00:00:04,562 --> 00:00:07,687
May 17, 2026  Week 20.

3
00:00:07,687 --> 00:00:08,650
TL;DR.

4
00:00:08,650 --> 00:00:25,250
$67B Market Cap on Day One: Cerebras debuts on Nasdaq, stock opens +108%, closes up +68% – the biggest tech IPO of 2026 confirms: AI infrastructure is the new gold

5
00:00:25,250 --> 00:00:40,237
Bank Accounts Inside ChatGPT: OpenAI connects its current ChatGPT model to 12,000+ financial institutions via Plaid – 200 million monthly finance questions now get real-time data .

6
00:00:40,237 --> 00:00:50,775
arXiv's Nuclear Option: A one-year ban for fully AI-written papers – the first major platform backlash against uncritical LLM use in academia

7
00:00:50,775 --> 00:01:05,437
OpenAI vs. Apple in Court: After a disappointing iOS integration, OpenAI is reportedly preparing legal action against Apple – the partnership announced at WWDC in June 2024 lies in ruins .

8
00:01:05,437 --> 00:01:15,200
Story of the Week: Cerebras IPO – $5.5B Raised, Stock Opens +108%, Closes +68%.

9
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:19,600
"A year ago, it looked like this day would never happen for Cerebras."

10
00:01:19,600 --> 00:01:25,175
– this TechCrunch line captures the story behind the most spectacular market debut of the year .

11
00:01:25,175 --> 00:01:35,962
On May 14, 2026, Cerebras Systems debuted on Nasdaq, raising $5.55 billion – the largest tech IPO of the current season.

12
00:01:35,962 --> 00:01:46,087
The offering price was set at $185 per share, well above the originally targeted range of $115 to $125.

13
00:01:46,087 --> 00:01:53,837
At the open, the stock traded at $385 – a gain of over 108% over the offering price.

14
00:01:53,837 --> 00:02:02,862
By the close at $311, the day's gain stood at +68% with a market cap of approximately $67 billion .

15
00:02:02,862 --> 00:02:04,112
What's behind the hype?

16
00:02:04,112 --> 00:02:13,100
Cerebras is not another generic AI startup, but a chip company with a radically different architecture: the Wafer-Scale Engine (WSE).

17
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:25,712
While NVIDIA produces GPUs as small squares on a silicon wafer, Cerebras uses the entire wafer as a single chip – with 2.6 trillion transistors and 40 GB of on-chip memory.

18
00:02:25,712 --> 00:02:31,962
This eliminates the most expensive bottleneck in AI inference: shuttling data between chips .

19
00:02:31,962 --> 00:02:47,487
The financials confirm this isn't just hot air: in 2025, Cerebras generated $510 million in revenue – 76% growth year-over-year – and recorded a net profit of $237.8 million .

20
00:02:47,487 --> 00:02:57,800
Founder Andrew Feldman holds personal wealth of approximately $1.9 billion after the IPO, with co-founder Sean Lie at around $1 billion.

21
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:01,600
For the industry, this IPO is more than a success story.

22
00:03:01,600 --> 00:03:12,175
It signals that the market believes inference hardware – not just training infrastructure – will become the next major bottleneck as AI usage spreads across billions of products.

23
00:03:12,175 --> 00:03:18,125
Whoever delivers the fastest and cheapest inference controls a critical layer of the AI stack.

24
00:03:18,125 --> 00:03:25,225
Cerebras is betting exactly on that – and the market validates the bet at a $67 billion valuation.

25
00:03:25,225 --> 00:03:34,687
That the IPO came after a lengthy regulatory run-up (Saudi investors had caused delays at an earlier stage ) makes the outcome all the more impressive.

26
00:03:34,687 --> 00:03:42,500
It's a sign that 2026 could go down in history as the year of AI IPOs – and Cerebras fired the starting gun.

27
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:52,037
One caveat worth noting: typical post-IPO dynamics such as lock-up expirations and profit-taking could pressure the valuation in the coming months.

28
00:03:52,037 --> 00:03:53,375
More Top Stories.

29
00:03:53,375 --> 00:03:59,175
ChatGPT Reaches Into Your Bank Accounts – OpenAI Launches Personal Finance Tools.

30
00:03:59,175 --> 00:04:04,575
OpenAI has begun transforming ChatGPT into a personal finance platform.

31
00:04:04,575 --> 00:04:21,262
Pro subscribers in the US can now connect their bank and investment accounts directly to ChatGPT – through Plaid integration, more than 12,000 financial institutions are accessible, including Charles Schwab, Fidelity, JPMorgan Chase, and American Express .

32
00:04:21,262 --> 00:04:29,425
The result is a dashboard showing portfolio performance, spending trends, active subscriptions, and upcoming payments at a glance.

33
00:04:29,425 --> 00:04:34,500
ChatGPT can then answer questions like: "Have I been spending more than usual lately?

34
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:35,450
What's changed?"

35
00:04:35,450 --> 00:04:39,350
– drawing on actual account data, not hypothetical scenarios .

36
00:04:39,350 --> 00:04:44,937
The model behind the feature is, according to OpenAI, the current ChatGPT model.

37
00:04:44,937 --> 00:04:51,425
OpenAI acquired the fintech startup Hiro, which provided the technological foundation for this integration.

38
00:04:51,425 --> 00:04:57,287
On privacy, account data is set to be fully deleted 30 days after disconnecting the account.

39
00:04:57,287 --> 00:05:02,612
OpenAI's next planned step is an Intuit integration for direct tax simulations .

40
00:05:03,537 --> 00:05:10,900
The context makes the scale clear: 200 million users ask ChatGPT about financial topics each month .

41
00:05:10,900 --> 00:05:15,987
Until now, those users were entering account numbers manually or estimating.

42
00:05:15,987 --> 00:05:17,812
Now real data flows in.

43
00:05:17,812 --> 00:05:31,575
This is the closest integration yet of a general-purpose LLM with critical financial infrastructure – and it opens a debate about privacy, liability, and whether a chat model should really serve as a financial advisor.

44
00:05:31,575 --> 00:05:37,475
arXiv Issues One-Year Bans for AI Ghostwriters – Academia Draws a Line

45
00:05:37,475 --> 00:05:51,437
arXiv, the world's most important preprint repository, has drawn a clear red line: anyone demonstrably submitting papers generated entirely by LLMs without critical review will face a one-year ban .

46
00:05:51,437 --> 00:06:00,237
The new "one-strike" rule is not aimed at AI assistance in general – writing aid, grammar correction, and structural feedback remain permitted.

47
00:06:00,237 --> 00:06:05,937
The line is drawn where authors pass through language model outputs without substantive review.

48
00:06:05,937 --> 00:06:22,750
Thomas Dietterich, chair of arXiv's computer science section, states the core issue plainly: "If a submission contains incontrovertible evidence that the authors did not check the results of LLM generation, this means we can't trust anything in the paper." .

49
00:06:22,750 --> 00:06:37,625
Concrete indicators of a policy violation include fabricated citations, hallucinations in factual claims, and unfiltered LLM boilerplate – often recognizable by characteristic phrases or systematically incorrect references.

50
00:06:37,625 --> 00:06:44,362
After serving the ban, authors can only return if their work has been accepted by established peer-reviewed publishers .

51
00:06:44,362 --> 00:06:46,700
The decision doesn't come in a vacuum.

52
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:53,262
Since 2023, arXiv has seen a flood of submissions with a recognizable AI fingerprint.

53
00:06:53,262 --> 00:07:03,787
For the academic community, this is the first high-profile institutional signal: AI use is not banned outright, but scientific accountability cannot be delegated.

54
00:07:03,787 --> 00:07:08,850
OpenAI Prepares Legal Action Against Apple – Failed Partnership Heads to Court.

55
00:07:08,850 --> 00:07:19,362
The ChatGPT integration into iOS, announced with much fanfare at WWDC in June 2024, is turning into an expensive legal dispute.

56
00:07:19,362 --> 00:07:26,312
According to consistent reports, OpenAI has engaged outside counsel to explore legal action against Apple .

57
00:07:26,312 --> 00:07:32,787
The crux of the conflict: OpenAI alleges that Apple actively undermined the ChatGPT integration.

58
00:07:32,787 --> 00:07:44,612
Features were "buried," visibility within the iOS ecosystem fell far short of expectations, and the resulting subscription numbers came in massively below internal projections.

59
00:07:44,612 --> 00:07:55,062
An OpenAI executive put it bluntly, as quoted by TechCrunch  (orig. Bloomberg): "They basically said, 'OpenAI needs to take a leap of faith and trust us.'

60
00:07:55,062 --> 00:07:56,550
It didn't work out well.".

61
00:07:56,550 --> 00:08:09,075
A number comparison illustrates the contrast: Apple reportedly pays Google approximately $1 billion annually for the Gemini integration – an amount that shows what Apple is willing to invest when it wants to .

62
00:08:09,075 --> 00:08:13,375
OpenAI instead received an integration with half-hearted placement.

63
00:08:13,375 --> 00:08:15,050
Apple sees things differently.

64
00:08:15,050 --> 00:08:26,525
Internally, the company is said to have raised substantial privacy concerns – a perspective that, given Apple's years-long privacy positioning, cannot be easily dismissed as a pretext.

65
00:08:26,525 --> 00:08:33,950
Tensions also arose around OpenAI's hardware ambitions (its own devices, potential competition with the iPhone).

66
00:08:33,950 --> 00:08:46,650
Regardless of the legal outcome, the conflict demonstrates: the negotiating position of AI labs against platform gatekeepers like Apple and Google is more complicated than the initial partnership euphoria suggested.

67
00:08:46,650 --> 00:08:47,600
Quick Hits.

68
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:59,337
Malta: First Government with ChatGPT Plus for All Citizens  – OpenAI and Malta have sealed a partnership providing all Maltese citizens with free ChatGPT Plus access.

69
00:08:59,337 --> 00:09:05,187
Malta is thereby the first government worldwide with state-funded universal AI access.

70
00:09:05,187 --> 00:09:15,325
A precedent with signal value for European AI strategies – though critics point to the resulting state dependency on a US company and open data privacy questions.

71
00:09:16,250 --> 00:09:37,050
Open-Source Boom: Gemma 4, DeepSeek V4, Kimi K2.6, and More  – Nathan Lambert of Interconnects describes an "eventful month" for open-weight models: Gemma 4, DeepSeek V4, Kimi K2.6, MiMo 2.5, and GLM-5.1 appeared in rapid succession.

72
00:09:37,050 --> 00:09:47,587
The gap to proprietary models continues to shrink – though open-weight models carry their own risks, including lack of quality control in fine-tuning and potential for misuse.

73
00:09:47,587 --> 00:10:01,325
Anthropic + Gates Foundation: $200M for Global Health and Education  – Over four years, $200 million will flow into a program targeting 4.6 billion people in low-income countries.

74
00:10:01,325 --> 00:10:06,712
Claude-powered tutoring tools for Sub-Saharan Africa and India are concretely planned.

75
00:10:06,712 --> 00:10:12,612
The program focuses on expanding global access to AI tools in underserved regions.

76
00:10:12,612 --> 00:10:19,837
Tool of the Week: NVIDIA SANA-WM – Open-Source World Model for 1-Minute Video in 720p.

77
00:10:19,837 --> 00:10:27,162
NVIDIA Labs has released SANA-WM, an open-source world model that takes video generation to a new level .

78
00:10:27,162 --> 00:10:28,200
What it does:.

79
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:32,475
Generates up to 60 seconds of video in 720p quality.

80
00:10:32,475 --> 00:10:38,950
2.6 billion parameters – large enough for high-quality outputs, small enough for broader deployment

81
00:10:38,950 --> 00:10:44,262
Direct competition to proprietary video generation models like Sora or Veo .

82
00:10:44,262 --> 00:10:45,600
What makes it special:.

83
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:57,025
The model operates as a true "world model" – it doesn't just understand pixels, but models physical relationships and temporal consistency across the entire video sequence.

84
00:10:57,025 --> 00:11:03,337
This distinguishes it from frame-by-frame approaches that often become inconsistent over longer clips.

85
00:11:03,337 --> 00:11:04,512
Why it matters:.

86
00:11:04,512 --> 00:11:10,250
Open-source video generation was until recently limited to short, low-resolution clips.

87
00:11:10,250 --> 00:11:12,850
SANA-WM breaks through that barrier.

88
00:11:12,850 --> 00:11:26,025
For content creators, developers, and researchers, this means: high-quality AI video generation without proprietary API dependency, without per-minute billing, and with the freedom for further development.

89
00:11:26,025 --> 00:11:32,950
NVIDIA demonstrates that open source is catching up in the video segment just as fast as it did with language models.

90
00:11:32,950 --> 00:11:39,750
Fail of the Week: Cisco Lays Off 4,000 Employees During Record Quarter – "To Invest in AI".

91
00:11:39,750 --> 00:11:46,562
Cisco has announced it will cut approximately 4,000 positions – about 5% of its total workforce .

92
00:11:46,562 --> 00:11:51,775
At the same time, the company reported record quarterly revenue and double-digit growth.

93
00:11:51,775 --> 00:12:02,350
CEO Chuck Robbins cited the need to free up capital for AI investments, while simultaneously announcing investment in "employees' use of AI across the company" .

94
00:12:02,350 --> 00:12:12,612
The irony could hardly be sharper: employees are being laid off so AI can take over their work – and the remaining employees are then expected to use AI themselves.

95
00:12:12,612 --> 00:12:14,125
Cisco is not alone.

96
00:12:14,125 --> 00:12:21,837
Cloudflare and General Motors have offered similar justifications for job cuts amid strong financial results in recent weeks.

97
00:12:21,837 --> 00:12:35,912
What's emerging here is a new corporate playbook: "AI pivot" as justification for cost reductions – regardless of whether actual AI productivity gains are replacing jobs or whether the goal is simply to optimize margins.

98
00:12:35,912 --> 00:12:43,212
A footnote worth mentioning: CEO Robbins' planned compensation for 2025 is $52 million .

99
00:12:43,212 --> 00:12:46,950
Number of the Week: $134 Billion.

100
00:12:46,950 --> 00:12:53,562
Elon Musk is seeking $134 billion in damages from OpenAI and Sam Altman .

101
00:12:53,562 --> 00:12:59,762
Closing arguments in the Musk vs. OpenAI/Altman trial were completed this week.

102
00:12:59,762 --> 00:13:06,537
Judge Yvonne Gonzalez Rogers will make the final decision – the jury serves only in an advisory capacity.

103
00:13:06,537 --> 00:13:09,112
Deliberation began early in the week.

104
00:13:09,112 --> 00:13:10,287
Why it matters:.

105
00:13:10,287 --> 00:13:17,275
$134 billion is less than half of OpenAI's current valuation (~$300B).

106
00:13:17,275 --> 00:13:24,187
Musk is demanding damages of historic magnitude – plus the removal of Sam Altman and the other founders.

107
00:13:24,187 --> 00:13:34,187
Regardless of the verdict, this trial is the first judicial examination of the question of whether nonprofit-to-for-profit conversions at AI companies are legitimate.

108
00:13:34,187 --> 00:13:38,162
The ruling will set precedent – for OpenAI and well beyond.

